@HouseScience @POTUS @realDonaldTrump I look forward to learning more today from our witnesses about this topic, about their efforts to advance understanding in this field, and about the technologies and methods that will lead the way to a better and smarter future.

@HouseScience @POTUS @realDonaldTrump Adverse space weather presents unique challenges & consequences of inaction could be catastrophic. However, I believe that through the right combination of government monitoring, private industry innovation & American determination, we can respond to any future challenges.
@HouseScience @POTUS @realDonaldTrump It is my hope that, on the subject of space weather, we will continue to look to that law as a model.

@HouseScience @POTUS @realDonaldTrump What I like most about this legislation is that it compels the government to innovate by partnering with the growing private sector to test and validate its data in order to enhance our nation’s forecasting capabilities.

@HouseScience Last year, @POTUS @realDonaldTrump signed into law the Weather Research and Forecasting Innovation Act, a comprehensive bill to increase our weather forecasting capabilities to better protect lives and property.

@HouseScience In the face of space weather challenges, instead of continuing to think inside the “government-only” box, NASA and NOAA need to look to private partners who are ready and willing to help.

@HouseScience Partners in the private sector can—and should—use their advanced and innovative technologies to help us more thoroughly understand these phenomena and improve our space weather predictions.

@HouseScience Forecasting space weather depends on understanding the fundamental processes that give rise to hazardous events.  Particularly important is the study of processes that link the Sun-Earth system and that control the flow of energy toward our planet.

@HouseScience I look forward to hearing from them about not only what their efforts have been in this arena, but also what they think the future holds for the observation, modeling, and forecasting of space weather events.

@HouseScience I am glad, then, to have key stakeholders from private industry as well as academia, along with leaders from the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, NOAA, and the National Aeronautics and Space Administration, NASA, with us here.

@HouseScience While all of these topics are important and worth addressing, I think it is crucial that we first lay the groundwork for understanding the current policies, procedures, and major players in both the private and public sectors.

@HouseScience There are many avenues we could explore for this hearing, from innovative space weather technologies and the accuracy of space weather forecasting models, to the potential impacts space weather can have on our terrestrial environment.
@HouseScience With an issue as complex and consequential as this one, it is undeniably important we begin a dialogue on what the status quo is and in what direction momentum is heading.

@HouseScience Good Morning, and welcome to today’s @HouseScience joint Environment and Space Subcommittee hearing, entitled “Surveying the Space Weather Landscape.”  I would like to first thank our excellent witnesses for being here today and for testifying on this important topic.

@HouseScience @POTUS Today we will hear ideas about how some of those fixes to the regulation should look.  Witnesses will inform Congress how federal water regulations affect them and what they need from the government to continue operating effectively. I look forward to a knowledgeable discussion.

@HouseScience @POTUS I applaud the Admin for heeding the calls of Americans. A revision to the rule is desperately needed to provide greater clarity to states. Instead of rushing forward with burdensome federal regulations, the gov needs to do its due diligence & propose a rule that is helpful.

@HouseScience The shortcomings of WOTUS are so self-evident that it is not surprising this onerous rule has been challenged across the country. And now we can point to a very encouraging action from the new admin: @POTUS recently issued an executive order to review the WOTUS rule.

@HouseScience Our nation depends on the hard work of farmers & ranchers: these men and women simply don’t have the time to deal with bureaucratic nonsense. Of course, it’s not just them who suffer:costly & unnecessary government mandates have drastic economic impacts on each & every one of us.

@HouseScience For example, when WOTUS was proposed there was a large outcry from stakeholders across the nation that the rule’s vague definitions regarding navigable water could include sometimes-dry drainage ditches on private farmland.  It is absurd to consider a dry ditch “navigable.”

@HouseScience We all want to be good stewards of the environment.  We also want to be good stewards for the people we represent.  When a federal agency overlooks the needs of U.S. citizens, we in Congress have a duty to ask questions & address the concerns of our constituents. @HouseScience

@HouseScience I am very pleased to have representatives here today from my home state of Arizona to discuss how this rule would affect them and what changes they believe would make water regulations better for this country.

@HouseScience WOTUS rule amounted to one of the biggest federal overreaches in modern history.  The rule’s flimsy definitions & underlying science means that the EPA had the ability to regulate private land & also placed significant financial burdens on some of our country’s hardest workers.

@HouseScience OPENING STATEMENT FOR @HouseScience subcommittee hearing: Welcome to today’s hearing, “The Future of WOTUS: Examining the Role of States.”  I want to thank our expert panel of witnesses for being here today and agreeing to testify about this important topic.

The #WOTUS rule imposed by Obama admin crippled states’ ability to regulate bodies of water. States should have this power, not Washington bureaucrats. Learn how @HouseScience is working to improve future federal water rules: https://t.co/dM4hodiQnV https://t.co/P1F8td4xbQ

ICYMI - my opening statement for today's joint @HouseScience subcommittee hearing on geoengineering: https://t.co/hlvSWcjED1 #AZ05
@HouseScience Again, I want to thank the witnesses for being here today, and I look forward to hearing more about these interesting concepts.
@HouseScience The purpose of this hearing is to discuss the viability of geoengineering and any early-stage research associated with this approach.
@HouseScience We have a responsibility to explore these concepts, learn as much as possible & discuss ideas to help support research.
@HouseScience Today, we will learn about what research has been conducted on geoengineering and which promising concepts should be explored further.
@HouseScience Since concepts involved are still so new, we cannot say definitively if geoengineering tech warrants full-scale development or deployment.
@HouseScience While there are at least a few programs in our nation’s universities looking into these concepts, federal research is still limited.
@HouseScience Avenues of geoengineering research & others are still in the developmental stage & any or all of them may warrant further exploration.
@HouseScience Geoengineering is the concept of using scientific understanding to alter the atmosphere in a way that produces positive outcomes & results.
@HouseScience Since this is the first time we are discussing geoengineering this Congress, it is important to explain what geoengineering actually is.
